<h1>Problem 2312 - 2022 Putnam, B4</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Find all integers \(n\) with \(n \geq 4\) for which there exists a sequence of distinct real numbers \(x_1,\dots,x_n\) such that each of the sets
\begin{gather*}
\{x_1,x_2,x_3\}, \{x_2,x_3,x_4\}, \dots, \{x_{n-2},x_{n-1},x_n\}, \{x_{n-1},x_n, x_1\}, \mbox{ and } \{x_n, x_1, x_2\}
\end{gather*}
forms a 3-term arithmetic progression when arranged in increasing order.</p>
